    <td class="align_top align_left what_is_pm_table_col2">
      <h4 class="bold">How can fine particles affect me?</h4>
      <p>
        Coarse particles that are between 2.5 and 10 micrometers in size are generally
        trapped by hairs and mucus in the nose and throat, but never make it as far as
        your lungs. Fine particles, on the other hand, are dangerous because they are
        small enough penetrate deep into the lungs, blocking the air sacs where oxygen
        enters the bloodstream. While particulates are
        generally not toxic, airborne toxic chemicals can attach to PM<sub>2.5</sub> and enter your
        bloodstream. Fine particulate pollution can also have environmental impacts including
        soil and water contamination.
      </p>
      <div class="learn_more"><a href="http://www.epa.gov/airquality/particulatematter/fastfacts.html" target="_blank">learn more</a></div>
